12/12/2002
SKOPJE, Macedonia -- NATO will continue to advise and assist in the implementation of reforms even after the EU takes over the operational part of the mission, NATO spokesman Mark Laity announced Wednesday (11 December). He added that the new NATO mission, Allied Harmony, would consist of 450 soldiers from NATO member states. It begins Sunday.
In other news, the mayors of Skopje and Moscow met Wednesday and signed a bilateral agreement on co-operation for the period of 2003 to 2006. It envisions exchanges in education, culture, sports and art and aims to intensify trade and economic relations. (A1 TV, Makfax, Dnevnik - 12/12/02; MIA, Makfax, A1 TV - 11/12/02)
